WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.437 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.437 --> 00:00:04.311 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.311 --> 00:00:05.269 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.269 --> 00:00:10.840 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:13.700 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: So at the
end of last lecture,

00:00:13.700 --> 00:00:19.420 align:middle line:84%
so we discussed this LSZ
theorem, which tells you

00:00:19.420 --> 00:00:26.740 align:middle line:84%
how to obtain scattering
amplitude from correlation

00:00:26.740 --> 00:00:30.170 align:middle line:84%
functions, from time-ordered
correlation functions.

00:00:30.170 --> 00:00:33.670 align:middle line:84%
OK, so if you want
to compute, say,

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:37.870 align:middle line:84%
some scattering amplitude from
alpha to beta-- so alpha's

00:00:37.870 --> 00:00:41.470 align:middle line:84%
some initial state and
beta's some final state.

00:00:41.470 --> 00:00:48.130 align:middle line:84%
Say alpha consists of
momentum p1 and PN--

00:00:48.130 --> 00:00:58.380 align:middle line:84%
or pm, and beta, say
momentum p m plus 1 and pn.

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:03.390 align:middle line:84%
And then you can get
this scattering amplitude

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:05.880 align:middle line:84%
just by taking your
momentum-space correlation

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:12.520 align:middle line:90%
function, OK, for the n points.

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:14.430 align:middle line:84%
So all together,
you have an n points

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:17.730 align:middle line:84%
for the external
momentum, OK, and then

00:01:17.730 --> 00:01:21.150 align:middle line:90%
you take the on-shell limit.

00:01:21.150 --> 00:01:23.880 align:middle line:84%
You take the on-shell
limit, and then that

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:36.950 align:middle line:84%
gives you the product of the
external propagators, then

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:40.830 align:middle line:90%
times the scattering amplitude.

00:01:40.830 --> 00:01:42.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:42.630 --> 00:01:46.080 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
relation, OK, so here I

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:48.960 align:middle line:84%
have stripped out the momentum
conservation on both sides.

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:51.390 align:middle line:84%
Of course, momentum
has to be conserved.

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:58.410 align:middle line:84%
Inside, the total
momentum has to be zero.

00:01:58.410 --> 00:02:05.010 align:middle line:84%
And so this limit is
the on-shell limit,

00:02:05.010 --> 00:02:13.010 align:middle line:84%
and in the on-shell limit,
the initial momentum--

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:16.400 align:middle line:84%
OK, actually, I should
call it minus p.

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:19.550 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, it's minus pm.

00:02:19.550 --> 00:02:23.750 align:middle line:84%
So the initial
momentum, for those

00:02:23.750 --> 00:02:28.280 align:middle line:84%
with the initial momentum,
you take p1 to be--

00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:34.130 align:middle line:90%
p1 0 to have minus omega p1, OK?

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:36.590 align:middle line:90%
For the final momentum--

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:37.505 align:middle line:90%
so p alpha.

00:02:37.505 --> 00:02:40.150 align:middle line:90%


00:02:40.150 --> 00:02:43.300 align:middle line:84%
For the final momentum,
you take the p beta

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:52.120 align:middle line:84%
0 goes to omega p beta, the
final, OK, with the plus sign.

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:55.180 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's how you
distinguish the initial state

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:59.890 align:middle line:84%
from the final state, because
when you obtain a correlation

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:02.890 align:middle line:84%
function, you don't
distinguish what

00:03:02.890 --> 00:03:04.680 align:middle line:84%
is the initial and
the final state.

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:07.400 align:middle line:90%
You just have some momentum.

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.930 align:middle line:84%
This is a function of
some arbitrary momentum.

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:13.690 align:middle line:84%
But the scattering
amplitude, of course,

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:18.850 align:middle line:84%
those momentum are on shell,
and so the way you distinguish

00:03:18.850 --> 00:03:21.670 align:middle line:84%
the initial momentum
and the final momentum

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:23.900 align:middle line:84%
is by taking the
initial momentum,

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:27.100 align:middle line:84%
say to go to the negative
root, and the final momentum

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:28.960 align:middle line:90%
to take the positive root.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:33.430 align:middle line:84%
But since the alpha, it
consists of minus p1, and then

00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:37.090 align:middle line:84%
the initial state, you
have positive energy, OK,

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:40.130 align:middle line:90%
you have positive energy.

00:03:40.130 --> 00:03:45.600 align:middle line:84%
So this tells you that when
we compute the scattering

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:46.280 align:middle line:90%
amplitude--

00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:51.180 align:middle line:90%


00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:56.815 align:middle line:84%
when we compute the scattering
amplitude, we should take the--

00:03:56.815 --> 00:04:00.250 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:08.070 align:middle line:84%
we just take all
the Feynman diagrams

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:11.280 align:middle line:84%
which you used to calculate
these correlation functions,

00:04:11.280 --> 00:04:13.245 align:middle line:90%
OK, and then you sum over--

00:04:13.245 --> 00:04:18.180 align:middle line:90%


00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:22.300 align:middle line:84%
you sum over, say,
the truncated--

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:27.270 align:middle line:90%


00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:31.410 align:middle line:84%
so you see the relation between
these correlation functions

00:04:31.410 --> 00:04:33.100 align:middle line:90%
and the scattering amplitudes.

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:37.030 align:middle line:90%
So they differ by this product.

00:04:37.030 --> 00:04:40.630 align:middle line:84%
They differ by this product of
the external propagators, OK,

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:45.850 align:middle line:84%
so for each external momentum--
so here there's a propagator,

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:50.122 align:middle line:84%
and just as if
that-- when you get--

00:04:50.122 --> 00:04:53.830 align:middle line:84%
so this scattering amplitude
was corresponding to this one

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:56.710 align:middle line:84%
with all external
propagators stripped.

00:04:56.710 --> 00:05:00.220 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's why you
consider the truncated diagram

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:02.200 align:middle line:84%
not including the
external propagators.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:04.900 align:middle line:90%


00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:06.340 align:middle line:90%
And you take it on shell.

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.890 align:middle line:90%


00:05:08.890 --> 00:05:12.640 align:middle line:84%
OK, and also, since
we are interested only

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:14.480 align:middle line:90%
in the process--

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:17.900 align:middle line:84%
which, all particles participate
in the scattering process--

00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:21.585 align:middle line:84%
so we also only consider
the connected diagrams.

00:05:21.585 --> 00:05:24.600 align:middle line:90%


00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:30.240 align:middle line:84%
OK, consider the
connected diagrams.

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:34.930 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this provides
a simplification,

00:05:34.930 --> 00:05:38.490 align:middle line:84%
so you get fewer diagrams
and simpler expression

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:41.970 align:middle line:84%
than you would have got from
calculating these correlation

00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:45.460 align:middle line:84%
functions, OK,
correlation functions.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:47.460 align:middle line:90%
So any questions on this?

00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:51.590 align:middle line:90%


00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:52.183 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:05:52.183 --> 00:05:53.600 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So can
you explain again

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.890 align:middle line:84%
