you have one branch

00:05:56.890 --> 00:05:57.890 align:middle line:90%
and then there's a loop?

00:05:57.890 --> 00:05:59.360 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:05:59.360 --> 00:06:02.900 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I will explain
that, but before that

00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:04.220 align:middle line:90%
do you have other questions?

00:06:04.220 --> 00:06:08.470 align:middle line:90%


00:06:08.470 --> 00:06:09.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:12.120 align:middle line:84%
So now I will
explain a few things.

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:17.170 align:middle line:84%
OK, the first thing is
this sign convention,

00:06:17.170 --> 00:06:18.813 align:middle line:90%
OK, this sign convention.

00:06:18.813 --> 00:06:25.920 align:middle line:90%


00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:34.980 align:middle line:84%
OK, so remember this
Gn, so let's go back

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:37.770 align:middle line:84%
to the definition of this
Gn, these momentum-space

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:38.970 align:middle line:90%
correlation functions.

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:42.760 align:middle line:90%


00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:45.450 align:middle line:84%
So this is obtained by
doing a Fourier transform.

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:52.130 align:middle line:90%


00:06:52.130 --> 00:07:03.880 align:middle line:84%
Say-- I think it
would be minus sign.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:06.370 align:middle line:84%
OK, by doing the
Fourier transform--

00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:20.433 align:middle line:90%


00:07:20.433 --> 00:07:21.850 align:middle line:84%
yeah, by doing a
Fourier transform

00:07:21.850 --> 00:07:24.972 align:middle line:84%
of your coordinate-space
correlation function,

00:07:24.972 --> 00:07:26.680 align:middle line:84%
the coordinate-space
correlation function

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:29.160 align:middle line:84%
can be written as
the following, OK,

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:33.540 align:middle line:90%
so you have phi x1 and phi xn.

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:36.020 align:middle line:90%


00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:36.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:42.110 align:middle line:90%


00:07:42.110 --> 00:07:52.530 align:middle line:84%
So now, for those to go
to the initial state,

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:54.090 align:middle line:84%
OK, for those to go
to initial state,

00:07:54.090 --> 00:07:58.380 align:middle line:84%
we start from alpha
to beta, so then you

00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:01.320 align:middle line:84%
want those phi corresponding
to the initial state

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:05.460 align:middle line:84%
to act on the right,
OK, to act on the right.

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And then you do the Fourier
transform, OK, and then

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:09.940 align:middle line:90%
you do the Fourier transform.

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:12.000 align:middle line:84%
So now let's just
consider one of them.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:13.500 align:middle line:84%
Let's just say
consider you have phi

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:17.040 align:middle line:84%
x for the initial state
acting on the right,

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:18.565 align:middle line:84%
and then you do a
Fourier transform.

00:08:18.565 --> 00:08:19.065 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:19.065 --> 00:08:23.700 align:middle line:90%


00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:27.710 align:middle line:90%
OK, you do a Fourier transform.

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:35.240 align:middle line:84%
And so this, if you just
record the mode expansion

00:08:35.240 --> 00:08:39.860 align:middle line:84%
for phi and the phi
contains a and a dagger--

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:42.650 align:middle line:84%
and the a pieces acting on the
zero will just give you zero,

00:08:42.650 --> 00:08:44.900 align:middle line:84%
so only a dagger
piece will survive.

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:48.590 align:middle line:84%
OK, and the a dagger
piece is multiplied by--

00:08:48.590 --> 00:08:56.870 align:middle line:84%
say you will have,
say, some k, and then

00:08:56.870 --> 00:09:03.860 align:middle line:90%
have i omega k t plus minus.

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:10.197 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, essentially-- yeah, let me
just write it in a simple way.

00:09:10.197 --> 00:09:11.530 align:middle line:90%
You just have exponential i k x.

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:14.470 align:middle line:90%


00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:19.620 align:middle line:84%
OK, I think it's the exponential
minus i k x, so you just get

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:22.620 align:middle line:90%
the exponential minus i k x.

00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:24.600 align:middle line:84%
OK, with k it's the
on-shell momentum,

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:28.680 align:middle line:90%
so k is given by omega k and k.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:30.895 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:30.895 --> 00:09:33.200 align:middle line:84%
So when phi x
acting on the zero,

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:36.420 align:middle line:84%
you keep the part which is
corresponding to the a dagger,

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:40.010 align:middle line:84%
and then you get a piece
proportional like this.

00:09:40.010 --> 00:09:44.030 align:middle line:84%
OK, and now when you do
the Fourier transform

00:09:44.030 --> 00:09:51.900 align:middle line:84%
and then you find just p, then
your p just equals to minus k.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:54.570 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's related
to the minus sign

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:56.850 align:middle line:84%
there, OK, related to
the minus sign there,

00:09:56.850 --> 00:10:02.100 align:middle line:84%
and also, when your p equal
to minus k, then that means p0

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:03.960 align:middle line:90%
is equal to minus k.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:07.770 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's where that sign
in the initial state come from.

00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:10.360 align:middle line:84%
And the same thing
with the final state,

00:10:10.360 --> 00:10:12.930 align:middle line:84%
so for the final state, then
you need to look at the phi

00:10:12.930 --> 00:10:17.850 align:middle line:84%
x acting on the left
to this, and then you

00:10:17.850 --> 00:10:20.920 align:middle line:90%
do the Fourier transform.

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:21.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:24.370 align:middle line:90%


00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:27.500 align:middle line:84%
You do the Fourier transform,
and then in this case,

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:29.500 align:middle line:90%
this becomes--

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:32.720 align:middle line:84%
on the left, it's the A
part acting on the left,

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:35.690 align:middle line:84%
so this gives you
k exponential i

00:10:35.690 --> 00:10:42.710 align:middle line:84%
k x, OK, is the a
acting on the left.

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:45.430 align:middle line:84%
And then when you do the
Fourier transform, then here it

00:10:45.430 --> 00:10:47.350 align:middle line:90%
gives p equal to k.

00:10:47.350 --> 00:10:51.460 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's why
in the final state,

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:55.690 align:middle line:84%
you just have p equal
to k, and then p0

00:10:55.690 --> 00:10:57.625 align:middle line:90%
is equal to just omega k.

00:10:57.625 --> 00:11:01.290 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this explains the sign.

00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:03.050 align:middle line:90%
So this explains the sign.

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:06.080 align:middle line:84%
It's just from whether you
act on the initial state

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:07.400 align:middle line:90%
or act on the final state.

00:11:07.400 --> 00:11:07.900 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:07.900 --> 00:11:12.360 align:middle line:90%


00:11:12.360 --> 00:11:13.380 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:14.930 align:middle line:90%
So-- yes?

00:11:14.930 --> 00:11:17.028 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Right, so
