OK, because they

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:46.870 align:middle line:90%
don't touch with the--

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:48.730 align:middle line:84%
they only-- yeah,
you can also-- yeah,

00:13:48.730 --> 00:13:51.670 align:middle line:84%
you can do it on
any of them, OK?

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:53.500 align:middle line:84%
So such kind of
diagrams, they only

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:56.260 align:middle line:84%
change the external propagator,
but since we truncate

00:13:56.260 --> 00:13:59.050 align:middle line:84%
the external
propagator, and then

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:02.470 align:middle line:84%
they don't matter at
all, OK, and it's all

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:04.590 align:middle line:90%
included in this diagram.

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:05.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:09.090 align:middle line:90%
So the reason is the following.

00:14:09.090 --> 00:14:10.500 align:middle line:90%
The reason is the following.

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:15.060 align:middle line:84%
All this diagram
do is just modify

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:18.450 align:middle line:84%
the properties of the
external propagator,

00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:22.500 align:middle line:84%
OK, modify the properties
of the external propagator.

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:25.980 align:middle line:84%
And the only way
all these diagrams

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:29.050 align:middle line:84%
can modify the
external propagators

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:32.630 align:middle line:84%
is to give you an
overall constant,

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:34.870 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's what this
Z is corresponding to.

00:14:34.870 --> 00:14:37.690 align:middle line:84%
So this Z essentially
just captures

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:40.540 align:middle line:84%
all these different
corrections, OK,

00:14:40.540 --> 00:14:42.850 align:middle line:90%
all these different corrections.

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:45.850 align:middle line:84%
And now you have
truncated them, and so you

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:47.350 align:middle line:90%
don't need to worry about them.

00:14:47.350 --> 00:14:48.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:48.890 --> 00:14:52.640 align:middle line:84%
So Z also has an expansion,
just 1 plus order lambda,

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:55.700 align:middle line:84%
et cetera, so the leading
order, so Z does not contribute.

00:14:55.700 --> 00:14:58.190 align:middle line:84%
OK, you can just set
it to 1, and when

00:14:58.190 --> 00:15:03.730 align:middle line:84%
you go to the higher order, then
the Z can make a contribution.

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:05.800 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you just need
to separately take

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:09.310 align:middle line:84%
into account the Z, and
there's no need to contribute--

00:15:09.310 --> 00:15:11.110 align:middle line:84%
to calculate those
things separately.

00:15:11.110 --> 00:15:11.872 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:15:11.872 --> 00:15:13.330 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: We also
truncate diagrams

00:15:13.330 --> 00:15:15.725 align:middle line:84%
with loops in two
different legs?

00:15:15.725 --> 00:15:16.350 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:15:16.350 --> 00:15:19.530 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, yeah, any of them,
you can do any number of--

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:23.190 align:middle line:84%
as far as they only
concern external legs,

00:15:23.190 --> 00:15:26.310 align:middle line:84%
it's fine, yeah,
because this only--

00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:29.370 align:middle line:84%
any of those corrections
only concerns one leg, yeah.

00:15:29.370 --> 00:15:30.330 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:15:30.330 --> 00:15:32.890 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But when calculating
the actual, let's say,

00:15:32.890 --> 00:15:34.650 align:middle line:84%
n-point function, we
have-- we're supposed

00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:35.550 align:middle line:90%
to include all of this?

00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:36.450 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: That's right, yeah.

00:15:36.450 --> 00:15:38.117 align:middle line:84%
When you calculate
the n-point function,

00:15:38.117 --> 00:15:40.215 align:middle line:84%
you have to include
all this, but when

00:15:40.215 --> 00:15:42.465 align:middle line:84%
you calculate scattering
amplitude, you don't need to.

00:15:42.465 --> 00:15:43.170 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Don't
need to, all right.

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:44.040 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Because in the
scattering amplitude,

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:46.350 align:middle line:84%
you literally divide by
the external propagator,

00:15:46.350 --> 00:15:50.940 align:middle line:90%
and all of these things, they--

00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:54.930 align:middle line:84%
yeah, all these things,
essentially, they

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:56.880 align:middle line:90%
just modify the--

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:59.040 align:middle line:84%
give you the correction
to the external propagator

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:01.350 align:middle line:84%
and include it in
that constant Z, yeah.

00:16:01.350 --> 00:16:04.080 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So is Z
the same or different

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:06.870 align:middle line:90%
for different processes?

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:08.870 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, Z is the same.

00:16:08.870 --> 00:16:12.250 align:middle line:84%
No, Z is the same for
different processes,

00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:14.320 align:middle line:84%
but it's different for
different particles.

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:16.450 align:middle line:84%
So here we only have
one type of particles,

00:16:16.450 --> 00:16:18.660 align:middle line:84%
so we only have
one Z. But if you

00:16:18.660 --> 00:16:20.193 align:middle line:84%
have two kinds of
particles, then z

00:16:20.193 --> 00:16:21.735 align:middle line:84%
is different for
different particles.

00:16:21.735 --> 00:16:22.443 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

00:16:22.443 --> 00:16:26.490 align:middle line:84%
So for example, for, let's
say, a fixed process,

00:16:26.490 --> 00:16:29.670 align:middle line:84%
let's say, like, 3 going
to 3, Z would be constant

00:16:29.670 --> 00:16:31.230 align:middle line:84%
for all choices of
momentum, right?

00:16:31.230 --> 00:16:32.010 align:middle line:90%
Am I correct to say that?

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:33.630 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah,
yeah, it's all-- yeah,

00:16:33.630 --> 00:16:34.830 align:middle line:84%
a constant for
all of them, yeah.

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:36.450 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: OK, yeah, because if
it depended on momentum, then

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:37.440 align:middle line:84%
it would be kind
of useless, right?

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:39.690 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: No, no, no, it
does not depend on momentum.

00:16:39.690 --> 00:16:43.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, this just-- correct.

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:47.010 align:middle line:84%
You see, all such things
don't change the momentum.

00:16:47.010 --> 00:16:48.330 align:middle line:90%
OK, the momentum don't change.

00:16:48.330 --> 00:16:49.750 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:50.560 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:52.990 align:middle line:84%
So we will not go
into details of the Z.

00:16:52.990 --> 00:16:56.650 align:middle line:84%
And that is in the
QFT2, and so we

00:16:56.650 --> 00:17:01.600 align:middle line:84%
will discuss how to
calculate this z in QFT2.

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:03.530 align:middle line:84%
But the leading order,
they don't matter,

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:04.960 align:middle line:90%
and so we will start with 1.

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:09.609 align:middle line:84%
So for our purpose,
actually, it's not important.

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:10.540 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:12.880 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there a physical
interpretation for what

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:14.765 align:middle line:90%
interactions are included in Z?

00:17:14.765 --> 00:17:15.390 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:17:15.390 --> 00:17:17.040 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this is the
self-interact-- yeah,

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:20.190 align:middle line:84%
just when the-- when you
have an interacting theory,

00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:23.200 align:middle line:84%
so the particle can
interact with itself, when

00:17:23.200 --> 00:17:26.325 align:middle line:84%
the particle
propagates, it actually

00:17:26.325 --> 00:17:27.950 align:middle line:84%
can interact with
the virtual particle.

00:17:27.950 --> 00:17:29.660 align:middle line:84%
It just all comes from
this kind of diagram.

00:17:29.660 --> 00:17:31.310 align:middle line:84%
You can have single
particle, and you

00:17:31.310 --> 00:17:34.070 align:middle line:84%
can have such a diagram like
this and all these diagrams.

00:17:34.070 --> 00:17:39.410 align:middle line:90%


00:17:39.410 --> 00:17:42.050 align:middle line:84%
Correspondingly, you have
a particle propagating,

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:44.900 align:middle line:84%
but that particle can interact
with the virtual particle,

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:47.190 align:middle line:90%
its own virtual particle.

00:17:47.190 --> 00:17:50.100 align:middle line:84%
OK, and so the rule
corresponding to the particle

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:52.390 align:middle line:90%
loop, it's--

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:54.670 align:middle line:84%
so this is the real
external particle,

00:17:54.670 --> 00:17:57.940 align:middle line:84%
but anything coming
in the loop, you

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:01.060 align:middle line:84%
can imagine how the virtual
particle which come out

00:18:01.060 --> 00:18:03.820 align:middle line:84%
from the vacuum, and then
this can be interpreted

00:18:03.820 --> 00:18:06.790 align:middle line:84%
as the particle interacting with
its own virtual particle, yes,

00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:08.750 align:middle line:84%
a virtual particle
coming out from the back.

00:18:08.750 --> 00:18:09.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:18:09.520 --> 00:18:14.080 align:middle line:84%
And so that, this
kind of interaction,

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:17.520 align:middle line:84%
will affect the property
of the propagation

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:22.740 align:middle line:84%
but can have the most
effect by prefactor,

00:18:22.740 --> 00:18:25.050 align:middle line:84%
but actually can
change the mass, too.

00:18:25.050 --> 00:18:28.200 align:middle line:84%
But for the-- oh, it can
correct for the mass--

00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:32.790 align:middle line:84%
and also, that's the
subject of the QFT2--

00:18:32.790 --> 00:18:34.560 align:middle line:84%
can correct for
the mass, I think

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:38.171 align:middle line:84%
at most can change the
overall factor by z.

00:18:38.171 --> 00:18:42.890 align:middle line:90%


00:18:42.890 --> 00:18:43.760 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:18:43.760 --> 00:18:47.420 align:middle line:90%


00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:47.920 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:48.220 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:48.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:51.320 align:middle line:90%


00:18:51.320 --> 00:18:51.850 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:54.230 align:middle line:84%
If you don't have
other questions,

00:18:54.230 --> 00:18:59.920 align:middle line:84%
so let's conclude our discussion
of chapter 3 on interacting

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:01.350 align:middle line:90%
theories.

00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:04.640 align:middle line:84%
So as I said before,
as I mentioned before,

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:09.580 align:middle line:84%
and now you are really
equipped with the technique,

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:14.530 align:middle line:84%
now in principle you can
treat any interacting theory.

00:19:14.530 --> 00:19:17.590 align:middle line:84%
So the technique, even though
we just used the scalar theory,

00:19:17.590 --> 00:19:19.390 align:middle line:90%
but the technique is the same.

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:23.350 align:middle line:84%
OK, just for different theory,
you have different details, OK,

00:19:23.350 --> 00:19:25.870 align:middle line:84%
and now you have
already equipped

00:19:25.870 --> 00:19:29.710 align:middle line:84%
the foundation, the
basic tools for dealing

00:19:29.710 --> 00:19:31.600 align:middle line:90%
with any interacting theory.

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:38.270 align:middle line:84%
And for the goal
of this course, we

00:19:38.270 --> 00:19:41.060 align:middle line:84%
want in the end to be able
to calculate the, say,

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:45.230 align:middle line:84%
interactions in quantum
electrodynamics, OK,

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:47.660 align:middle line:84%
and for that purpose,
we still need

00:19:47.660 --> 00:19:50.600 align:middle line:90%
to have some other preparations.

00:19:50.600 --> 00:19:54.110 align:middle line:84%
So now let's discuss how
to describe fermions.

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:57.630 align:middle line:84%
OK, and now we've
described the scalar

00:19:57.630 --> 00:20:00.570 align:middle line:84%
and how the scalars
interact, and now we'll

00:20:00.570 --> 00:20:01.530 align:middle line:90%
talk about fermions.

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:08.700 align:middle line:90%


00:20:08.700 --> 00:20:10.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:10.950 --> 00:20:13.080 align:middle line:84%
So let me say a
little bit of history.

00:20:13.080 --> 00:20:16.770 align:middle line:90%


00:20:16.770 --> 00:20:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So, soon after the
quantum mechanics

00:20:20.790 --> 00:20:23.700 align:middle line:84%
was proposed by
Schrodinger and Heisenberg,

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:27.870 align:middle line:84%
et cetera, and then
people tried to generalize

00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:29.530 align:middle line:90%
to relativistic situation--

00:20:29.530 --> 00:20:32.350 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that came from this
Klein-Gordon equation,

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:35.490 align:middle line:84%
which we discussed
before, which in--

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:41.400 align:middle line:84%
this was the first attempt
to write down a wave equation

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:43.020 align:middle line:90%
for relativistic particles.

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:45.540 align:middle line:84%
OK, and we discussed
before, this

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:49.980 align:middle line:84%
does not really make sense as a
relativistic quantum mechanics.

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:58.160 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, yeah, but at the time,
this Klein-Gordon equation,

00:20:58.160 --> 00:21:02.150 align:middle line:84%
if you interpret it as a
wave equation, suffers some--

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:03.740 align:middle line:90%
suffers from some difficulties.

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:08.770 align:middle line:84%
One is that it does not
have a positive probability.

00:21:08.770 --> 00:21:13.600 align:middle line:90%


00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:15.040 align:middle line:90%
You cannot define--

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:28.790 align:middle line:84%
I should say cannot define
positive definite probability.

00:21:28.790 --> 00:21:41.410 align:middle line:90%


00:21:41.410 --> 00:21:44.350 align:middle line:84%
And the second difficulty is
that it has negative energy

00:21:44.350 --> 00:21:46.610 align:middle line:90%
state.

00:21:46.610 --> 00:21:47.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:47.110 --> 00:21:56.090 align:middle line:90%


00:21:56.090 --> 00:22:00.200 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, of course,
as I mentioned before,

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:02.030 align:middle line:90%
that this was--

00:22:02.030 --> 00:22:05.420 align:middle line:84%
there's more fundamental
reason that actually

00:22:05.420 --> 00:22:09.390 align:middle line:84%
relativistic quantum
mechanics does not make sense,

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:12.710 align:middle line:84%
but at the time,
in the late 1920s,

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:14.300 align:middle line:90%
people didn't realize that.

00:22:14.300 --> 00:22:17.480 align:middle line:84%
OK, people just looked
at those difficulties,

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:19.410 align:middle line:84%
they thought it's a
technical difficulty.

00:22:19.410 --> 00:22:23.540 align:middle line:84%
So Dirac proceeded trying to
correct those difficulties,

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:25.040 align:middle line:90%
to overcome those difficulties.

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:28.650 align:middle line:90%
OK, so Dirac then soon came up--

00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:35.420 align:middle line:84%
so I think this is around
1926, and then 1928, then Dirac

00:22:35.420 --> 00:22:41.590 align:middle line:84%
came up with this Dirac
theory, this Dirac equation.

00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:46.650 align:middle line:84%
OK, so Dirac equation was
aimed to cure those problems,

00:22:46.650 --> 00:22:51.790 align:middle line:84%
OK, so Dirac concluded that
the Klein-Gordon equation,

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:54.960 align:middle line:84%
the reason it had
those problems was

00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:56.640 align:middle line:84%
because the Klein-Gordon
equation has

00:22:56.640 --> 00:22:59.740 align:middle line:90%
a second-order derivative.

00:22:59.740 --> 00:23:03.000 align:middle line:84%
And then he said, if
we have a first-order--

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.240 align:middle line:84%
have an equation with
first-order-- yeah,

00:23:05.240 --> 00:23:08.365 align:middle line:84%
he speculated, if we
had the equation with

00:23:08.365 --> 00:23:10.740 align:middle line:84%
first-order-in-time derivative,
just like the Schrodinger

00:23:10.740 --> 00:23:14.940 align:middle line:84%
equation, and then both problems
maybe can be solved, OK,

00:23:14.940 --> 00:23:15.810 align:middle line:90%
can be solved.

00:23:15.810 --> 00:23:22.540 align:middle line:84%
And then Dirac came up
with the Dirac equation.

00:23:22.540 --> 00:23:24.180 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out that
the Dirac equation

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:28.390 align:middle line:84%
solved the first problem,
OK, but didn't really solve

00:23:28.390 --> 00:23:29.350 align:middle line:90%
the second problem.

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:34.420 align:middle line:84%
OK, but the level is, again,
due to more fundamental reasons,

00:23:34.420 --> 00:23:37.570 align:middle line:84%
you cannot really interpret
the Dirac equation

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:40.695 align:middle line:84%
as a relativistic quantum
mechanics equation,

00:23:40.695 --> 00:23:42.820 align:middle line:84%
a wave equation for
relativistic quantum mechanics.

00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:45.040 align:middle line:84%
Actually, the Dirac
equation should be

00:23:45.040 --> 00:23:46.720 align:middle line:90%
interpreted as a field theory.

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:50.290 align:middle line:84%
So nowadays, we interpret this
this is the-- gives the field

00:23:50.290 --> 00:23:59.710 align:middle line:90%
theory for--

00:23:59.710 --> 00:24:07.960 align:middle line:90%


00:24:07.960 --> 00:24:11.300 align:middle line:84%
OK, so of course,
Dirac didn't know this,

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:13.900 align:middle line:84%
so essentially, he discovered
this beautiful theory

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:17.320 align:middle line:84%
for the wrong motivation,
OK, for the wrong motivation.

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:22.870 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, this happens over
and over again in physics.

00:24:22.870 --> 00:24:24.850 align:middle line:90%
OK, people make great--

00:24:24.850 --> 00:24:30.610 align:middle line:84%
made great discoveries often
for the wrong motivations.

00:24:30.610 --> 00:24:33.920 align:middle line:84%
But the key is that if
you are good enough,

00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:36.250 align:middle line:84%
you will find something
new and that something new

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:36.910 align:middle line:90%
will be useful.

00:24:36.910 --> 00:24:44.410 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] OK, and this Dirac
theory is a prime example which

00:24:44.410 --> 00:24:47.410 align:middle line:84%
is actually one of
the most beautiful--

00:24:47.410 --> 00:24:50.740 align:middle line:84%
we will see, this is one of
the most beautiful equations

00:24:50.740 --> 00:24:53.740 align:middle line:90%
in mathematical physics.

00:24:53.740 --> 00:24:56.780 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, but also, it's actually
describing electrons,

00:24:56.780 --> 00:25:00.810 align:middle line:84%
so it's not only beautiful,
but it's actually useful.

00:25:00.810 --> 00:25:06.900 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this, first,
I'll talk about,

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:15.840 align:middle line:84%
introduce the Dirac equation,
OK, and its covariance.

00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:21.730 align:middle line:90%


00:25:21.730 --> 00:25:26.860 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the best way to
introduce the Dirac equation

00:25:26.860 --> 00:25:30.850 align:middle line:84%
was still his
original motivation,

00:25:30.850 --> 00:25:36.310 align:middle line:84%
is that we want to find the
first-order equation which

00:25:36.310 --> 00:25:37.670 align:middle line:90%
is Lorentz invariant.

00:25:37.670 --> 00:25:42.380 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the goal is that you
write down the equation,

00:25:42.380 --> 00:25:45.110 align:middle line:84%
like a Schrodinger equation,
which is first-order-in-time

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:54.890 align:middle line:84%
derivative, OK, but
is Lorentz covariant.

00:25:54.890 --> 00:25:59.350 align:middle line:90%


00:25:59.350 --> 00:26:01.990 align:middle line:90%
OK, but it's Lorentz covariant.

00:26:01.990 --> 00:26:03.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:09.420 align:middle line:84%
So but Lorentz covariant
means that this equation

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:12.760 align:middle line:84%
has the same form when you
go to a different frame.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:15.540 align:middle line:84%
OK, yeah, that's
what we mean by--

00:26:15.540 --> 00:26:18.060 align:middle line:84%
just when you go to a different
Lorentz frame, the equation,

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:20.340 align:middle line:84%
the form of the
equation looks the same.

00:26:20.340 --> 00:26:22.890 align:middle line:84%
Just different observers
in different laboratory,

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:25.200 align:middle line:84%
they see the same equation,
OK, so that's what

00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:28.410 align:middle line:90%
we mean by Lorentz covariant.

00:26:28.410 --> 00:26:32.550 align:middle line:84%
OK, so but for this to
be Lorentz covariant,

00:26:32.550 --> 00:26:36.180 align:middle line:84%
remember, Lorentz
transformation transform t to x,

00:26:36.180 --> 00:26:40.410 align:middle line:84%
so immediately,
you conclude that H

00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:49.440 align:middle line:84%
must be first-order in
spatial derivatives.

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:59.230 align:middle line:90%


00:26:59.230 --> 00:27:01.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:01.890 --> 00:27:08.740 align:middle line:84%
So the only-- then the most
general way you can write it,

00:27:08.740 --> 00:27:12.540 align:middle line:84%
so let's try to write
the most general--

00:27:12.540 --> 00:27:13.170 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:15.820 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, let's try to write
something like that.

00:27:15.820 --> 00:27:18.210 align:middle line:84%
So your first-order
derivative, then,

00:27:18.210 --> 00:27:25.350 align:middle line:84%
has to have the following
form, alpha minus i--

00:27:25.350 --> 00:27:30.390 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so this is the
gradient operator, yeah,

00:27:30.390 --> 00:27:33.790 align:middle line:84%
spatial derivatives, and yeah,
that's i just for convenience.

00:27:33.790 --> 00:27:36.600 align:middle line:84%
And then this is a vector,
have three components,

00:27:36.600 --> 00:27:38.580 align:middle line:84%
and then have to
contract with something,

00:27:38.580 --> 00:27:40.140 align:middle line:90%
and then we include the alpha.

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:44.700 align:middle line:84%
And then you can at most add
the constant, OK, so let me just

00:27:44.700 --> 00:27:47.100 align:middle line:84%
write this-- for
historical reasons,

00:27:47.100 --> 00:27:49.150 align:middle line:84%
write this constant
as m times beta.

00:27:49.150 --> 00:27:49.650 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:53.860 align:middle line:90%


00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:59.390 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at
this equation form,

00:27:59.390 --> 00:28:01.790 align:middle line:84%
you say this doesn't
make any sense, OK?

00:28:01.790 --> 00:28:08.660 align:middle line:84%
So alpha and beta, they have to
be some kind of constant, OK,

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:12.000 align:middle line:84%
but if alpha and
beta are constant,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.520 align:middle line:84%
then this is not even a
rotational invariant, not

00:28:15.520 --> 00:28:18.130 align:middle line:84%
to mention Lorentz
environment, OK,

00:28:18.130 --> 00:28:23.980 align:middle line:84%
because this derivative is not
contracted by any other Lorentz

00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:24.910 align:middle line:90%
indices.

00:28:24.910 --> 00:28:26.590 align:middle line:84%
So alpha is just
some constant, OK,

00:28:26.590 --> 00:28:39.430 align:middle line:84%
so this cannot be
Lorentz covariant,

00:28:39.430 --> 00:28:47.750 align:middle line:84%
even cannot be rotational
environment, OK,

00:28:47.750 --> 00:28:51.605 align:middle line:90%
if alpha or beta are constant.

00:28:51.605 --> 00:29:01.310 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.310 --> 00:29:09.710 align:middle line:84%
OK, and psi is the
ordinary function.

00:29:09.710 --> 00:29:18.953 align:middle line:90%


00:29:18.953 --> 00:29:19.453 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:19.453 --> 00:29:21.960 align:middle line:90%


00:29:21.960 --> 00:29:28.500 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, so you can have
alpha x, partial x, alpha

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:30.570 align:middle line:84%
y, partial y,
alpha z, partial z,

00:29:30.570 --> 00:29:34.620 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you can easily convince
yourself, when you rotate xyz,

00:29:34.620 --> 00:29:39.340 align:middle line:84%
this is not symmetric because
alpha is some constant.

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:43.540 align:middle line:84%
And so I'm sure this idea
came to many people trying

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:47.500 align:middle line:84%
to look for some first-order
equation which are Lorentz

00:29:47.500 --> 00:29:51.860 align:middle line:84%
covariant, then
after five minutes,

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:54.860 align:middle line:84%
you realize this
is not possible.

00:29:54.860 --> 00:29:58.730 align:middle line:84%
OK, this is just so simple,
it's just not possible.

00:29:58.730 --> 00:30:00.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:03.870 align:middle line:90%
But then Dirac made it work.

00:30:03.870 --> 00:30:06.747 align:middle line:84%
OK, it's really, say,
a stroke of genius.

00:30:06.747 --> 00:30:08.580 align:middle line:84%
It's really a stroke
of genius because there

00:30:08.580 --> 00:30:11.700 align:middle line:90%
was nothing like this before.

00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:13.740 align:middle line:84%
Just even from a
mathematical point of view,

00:30:13.740 --> 00:30:16.320 align:middle line:84%
it's purely, purely
imaginative, OK,

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:18.240 align:middle line:90%
just nothing like this before.

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:20.850 align:middle line:84%
Like when Einstein wrote
down his theory, et cetera,

00:30:20.850 --> 00:30:22.230 align:middle line:90%
you can still trace--

00:30:22.230 --> 00:30:25.470 align:middle line:84%
there some clues,
OK, but when Dirac--

00:30:25.470 --> 00:30:26.970 align:middle line:90%
this one just really--

00:30:26.970 --> 00:30:28.020 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:28.020 --> 00:30:31.950 align:middle line:84%
--like music, just came
out from his mind, OK?

00:30:31.950 --> 00:30:37.050 align:middle line:84%
It just-- and then
he reasoned, OK,

00:30:37.050 --> 00:30:40.890 align:middle line:84%
if this is constant
which does not work,

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:48.200 align:middle line:84%
and then let's make alpha
and beta to be matrices.

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:51.660 align:middle line:90%


00:30:51.660 --> 00:31:02.840 align:middle line:84%
Take them-- OK,
and then, so let's

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:04.730 align:middle line:90%
say they are n-by-n matrices.

00:31:04.730 --> 00:31:07.930 align:middle line:90%


00:31:07.930 --> 00:31:11.410 align:middle line:84%
Then in order for that
equation to make sense,

00:31:11.410 --> 00:31:14.320 align:middle line:84%
then psi has to be a
n-component vector.

00:31:14.320 --> 00:31:23.740 align:middle line:90%


00:31:23.740 --> 00:31:26.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:26.210 --> 00:31:32.890 align:middle line:84%
So even for some people,
you come up with this idea,

00:31:32.890 --> 00:31:34.390 align:middle line:84%
you will not imagine
this will work.

00:31:34.390 --> 00:31:36.860 align:middle line:84%
OK, you just say, oh,
this will be a mess,

00:31:36.860 --> 00:31:38.400 align:middle line:90%
but somehow, he made it work.

00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:41.370 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we will see
how to make this work.

00:31:41.370 --> 00:31:49.760 align:middle line:84%
And so now if you want
H to be Hermitian,

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:51.530 align:middle line:84%
and then you can
immediately conclude--

00:31:51.530 --> 00:31:54.530 align:middle line:84%
so that's why I put
the minus i thing here,

00:31:54.530 --> 00:31:56.225 align:middle line:90%
is the alpha and the beta.

00:31:56.225 --> 00:31:58.820 align:middle line:90%


00:31:58.820 --> 00:32:03.320 align:middle line:84%
So m will just be some constant,
OK, and here is a matrix.

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:06.350 align:middle line:84%
You can always take a
constant out, OK, so alpha,

00:32:06.350 --> 00:32:08.345 align:middle line:90%
beta are Hermitian matrices.

00:32:08.345 --> 00:32:13.958 align:middle line:90%


00:32:13.958 --> 00:32:15.875 align:middle line:84%
They're just some constant
Hermitian matrices.

00:32:15.875 --> 00:32:21.630 align:middle line:90%


00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:34.890 align:middle line:84%
And then, so then he reasoned
that for this equation,

00:32:34.890 --> 00:32:39.290 align:middle line:84%
if we want this equation
to be Lorentz covariant,

00:32:39.290 --> 00:32:43.520 align:middle line:84%
then at least it should
have the relativistic plane

00:32:43.520 --> 00:32:46.130 align:middle line:90%
wave as its solution.

00:32:46.130 --> 00:32:48.920 align:middle line:84%
OK, if you have a covariant
equation, and at least

00:32:48.920 --> 00:32:53.570 align:middle line:84%
you should have the relativistic
plane wave as its solution.

00:32:53.570 --> 00:32:57.380 align:middle line:84%
If it does not even have that
type of solution, then you,

00:32:57.380 --> 00:32:59.660 align:middle line:84%
yeah, of course
cannot be covariant.

00:32:59.660 --> 00:33:01.850 align:middle line:90%
OK, so the minimal requirement--

00:33:01.850 --> 00:33:06.010 align:middle line:90%


00:33:06.010 --> 00:33:09.330 align:middle line:84%
so before we really try to
see how can we make this

00:33:09.330 --> 00:33:12.810 align:middle line:84%
into a covariant equation,
we say let's consider

00:33:12.810 --> 00:33:14.040 align:middle line:90%
minimal requirement.

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:20.950 align:middle line:90%


00:33:20.950 --> 00:33:24.285 align:middle line:84%
So we'd like to-- here, let
me call this equation star.

00:33:24.285 --> 00:33:31.030 align:middle line:90%


00:33:31.030 --> 00:33:47.962 align:middle line:84%
Star should have
plane wave solutions

00:33:47.962 --> 00:34:02.630 align:middle line:84%
with the standard relativistic
dispersion relation, OK?

00:34:02.630 --> 00:34:13.159 align:middle line:90%


00:34:13.159 --> 00:34:15.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, these, you should have
p squared equal to minus m

00:34:15.560 --> 00:34:16.850 align:middle line:90%
squared.

00:34:16.850 --> 00:34:18.110 align:middle line:90%
OK, you have a plane wave.

00:34:18.110 --> 00:34:20.989 align:middle line:84%
The plane wave will
be labeled by p,

00:34:20.989 --> 00:34:22.460 align:middle line:84%
and then you should
have p squared

00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:23.510 align:middle line:90%
equal to minus m squared.

00:34:23.510 --> 00:34:29.980 align:middle line:84%
Then the m will be its
mass, OK, its mass.

00:34:29.980 --> 00:34:34.239 align:middle line:84%
And to do this, the
simplest way to do this,

00:34:34.239 --> 00:34:36.449 align:middle line:84%
so we know that the
Klein-Gordon equation--

00:34:36.449 --> 00:34:39.139 align:middle line:90%


00:34:39.139 --> 00:34:43.179 align:middle line:84%
so we know the Klein-Gordon
equation have such solutions.

00:34:43.179 --> 00:34:46.630 align:middle line:84%
OK, Klein-Gordon equation
have such solutions.

00:34:46.630 --> 00:34:51.370 align:middle line:84%
And then the simplest
way to do this is--

00:34:51.370 --> 00:34:53.380 align:middle line:84%
this is the
first-order equation.

00:34:53.380 --> 00:34:56.750 align:middle line:84%
And now imagine if we
square this equation,

00:34:56.750 --> 00:35:00.200 align:middle line:84%
and then this should reduce
to the Klein-Gordon equation.

00:35:00.200 --> 00:35:03.320 align:middle line:84%
If you can make that
work, then this property

00:35:03.320 --> 00:35:05.270 align:middle line:90%
will be satisfied, OK?

00:35:05.270 --> 00:35:10.190 align:middle line:90%
So this will be satisfied--

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:17.450 align:middle line:84%
can be satisfied
if square of star,

00:35:17.450 --> 00:35:28.375 align:middle line:84%
OK, satisfies reduced to
the Klein-Gordon equation.

00:35:28.375 --> 00:35:31.440 align:middle line:90%


00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:34.830 align:middle line:90%
OK, so now let's try to do this.

00:35:34.830 --> 00:35:37.010 align:middle line:84%
So when we square
this star, we just

00:35:37.010 --> 00:35:40.390 align:middle line:84%
act twice, so
essentially, you have--

00:35:40.390 --> 00:36:05.880 align:middle line:90%


00:36:05.880 --> 00:36:09.780 align:middle line:84%
so you have-- so when
you square that equation,

00:36:09.780 --> 00:36:14.070 align:middle line:84%
then you just get partial
partial t square psi

00:36:14.070 --> 00:36:16.710 align:middle line:90%
equal to H square psi.

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:22.140 align:middle line:84%
OK, and then we try to make
this of this Klein-Gordon form.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:29.070 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the right-hand side,
we just have the form minus i

00:36:29.070 --> 00:36:38.820 align:middle line:84%
with alpha dot with this, and
then plus beta m square psi.

00:36:38.820 --> 00:36:45.410 align:middle line:84%
OK, we have these, and then
you can just expand this

00:36:45.410 --> 00:36:50.015 align:middle line:84%
explicitly, so the right-hand
side, so then we have minus--

00:36:50.015 --> 00:36:53.100 align:middle line:90%


00:36:53.100 --> 00:36:59.130 align:middle line:84%
let's square this first-- then
you have minus alpha i alpha j.

00:36:59.130 --> 00:37:00.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:00.930 --> 00:37:07.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you have partial
partial xi partial partial xj

00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:10.430 align:middle line:90%
psi, and then let's square this.

00:37:10.430 --> 00:37:15.530 align:middle line:84%
Then you have beta
square m square psi,

00:37:15.530 --> 00:37:18.230 align:middle line:90%
and then you have cross term.

00:37:18.230 --> 00:37:25.460 align:middle line:84%
So cross term now has the form
beta alpha i plus alpha i beta.

00:37:25.460 --> 00:37:28.250 align:middle line:84%
But now remember, beta and
alpha, they are not constant.

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:31.460 align:middle line:84%
They are matrices, OK, so they
don't necessarily commute.

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:34.550 align:middle line:84%
So you have to be
careful about the orders.

00:37:34.550 --> 00:37:40.730 align:middle line:84%
OK, and m partial
psi partial xi.

00:37:40.730 --> 00:37:42.560 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the right-hand
side is just

00:37:42.560 --> 00:37:44.120 align:middle line:90%
like this when you square it.

00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:50.030 align:middle line:90%


00:37:50.030 --> 00:37:52.670 align:middle line:84%
And now we wanted to look at
the Klein-Gordon equation.

00:37:52.670 --> 00:37:55.410 align:middle line:84%
The Klein-Gordon equation
has the following form.

00:37:55.410 --> 00:37:58.980 align:middle line:90%
So now we want it to be--

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:07.080 align:middle line:84%
OK, hopefully to be given by
minus partial x square psi plus

00:38:07.080 --> 00:38:08.280 align:middle line:90%
m square psi.

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:12.060 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this one would be the
Klein-Gordon equation, OK,

00:38:12.060 --> 00:38:14.420 align:middle line:90%
which we wrote before.

00:38:14.420 --> 00:38:20.810 align:middle line:84%
OK, so by x-- yeah, here,
sorry, I should say xi square.

00:38:20.810 --> 00:38:25.170 align:middle line:90%


00:38:25.170 --> 00:38:26.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:38:26.070 --> 00:38:28.290 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:38:28.290 --> 00:38:29.905 align:middle line:90%
So i should be summed, OK?

00:38:29.905 --> 00:38:35.680 align:middle line:90%


00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:39.970 align:middle line:84%
So now we want this equation,
so we want the right-hand side

00:38:39.970 --> 00:38:42.440 align:middle line:90%
to be equal to this equation.

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:46.220 align:middle line:84%
If that works, then we're
guaranteed to have a plane-wave

00:38:46.220 --> 00:38:49.910 align:middle line:84%
solution of such a dispersion
relation because this equation

00:38:49.910 --> 00:38:51.110 align:middle line:90%
has--

00:38:51.110 --> 00:38:55.258 align:middle line:84%
OK, because this equation
has the plane-wave equation

00:38:55.258 --> 00:38:57.800 align:middle line:84%
with-- yeah, plane-wave solution
with that kind of dispersion

00:38:57.800 --> 00:38:59.010 align:middle line:90%
relation.

00:38:59.010 --> 00:39:03.290 align:middle line:84%
So now we just compare the
both sides, so for this

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:14.650 align:middle line:84%
to be true, so we
just need to have--

00:39:14.650 --> 00:39:17.800 align:middle line:84%
so let's compare the
second-order derivative term.

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:22.700 align:middle line:84%
And then we need
alpha i, so we need--

00:39:22.700 --> 00:39:27.300 align:middle line:90%


00:39:27.300 --> 00:39:33.530 align:middle line:84%
first, when i not equal to
j, the off-diagonal terms,

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:36.250 align:middle line:84%
they all should vanish,
OK, because here there's

00:39:36.250 --> 00:39:37.840 align:middle line:90%
only diagonal terms.

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:46.960 align:middle line:84%
So that means that the alpha
i alpha j plus alpha j alpha i

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:48.790 align:middle line:90%
should equal to 0.

00:39:48.790 --> 00:39:51.280 align:middle line:84%
OK, remember, the
matrices, they don't

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:53.770 align:middle line:84%
commute, so we should be
careful about the ordering.

00:39:53.770 --> 00:40:04.380 align:middle line:84%
OK, so when i not equal to
j and when i equal to j,

00:40:04.380 --> 00:40:06.360 align:middle line:84%
then you should
just reduce to here.

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:11.950 align:middle line:84%
OK, and that means that
the alpha i square should

00:40:11.950 --> 00:40:12.940 align:middle line:90%
equal to--

00:40:12.940 --> 00:40:14.770 align:middle line:90%
and here you should just--

00:40:14.770 --> 00:40:16.060 align:middle line:90%
here you should just--

00:40:16.060 --> 00:40:20.200 align:middle line:84%
this term just will
give that, and the--

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:22.600 align:middle line:84%
should equal to beta
square equal to 1.

00:40:22.600 --> 00:40:24.520 align:middle line:84%
OK, so here, there's
no summation, OK,

00:40:24.520 --> 00:40:25.840 align:middle line:90%
no summation over i.

00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:31.280 align:middle line:90%


00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:37.230 align:middle line:84%
OK, so each alpha i
square has to be 0,

00:40:37.230 --> 00:40:39.540 align:middle line:84%
and now we want this
linear term to be 0.

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:42.330 align:middle line:90%


00:40:42.330 --> 00:40:55.040 align:middle line:84%
And then you want beta alpha i
plus alpha i beta to be 0, OK?

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:58.160 align:middle line:84%
And also, just let
me put it together.

00:40:58.160 --> 00:41:02.360 align:middle line:84%
We said the alpha and the
beta, they must be Hermitian,

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:09.380 align:middle line:84%
so that means that the alpha
i dagger is equal to alpha i

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:12.590 align:middle line:84%
and the beta dagger
equal to beta.

00:41:12.590 --> 00:41:17.030 align:middle line:90%


