00:52:23.810 --> 00:52:28.710 align:middle line:84%
partial mu minus
m psi equal to 0.

00:52:28.710 --> 00:52:31.940 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is the form
of our Dirac equation.

00:52:31.940 --> 00:52:37.850 align:middle line:90%


00:52:37.850 --> 00:52:43.690 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this becomes
gamma 0 times partial t,

00:52:43.690 --> 00:52:47.480 align:middle line:84%
so this becomes gamma
i times partial xi.

00:52:47.480 --> 00:52:51.160 align:middle line:84%
When they come together, then
become gamma mu partial mu,

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:54.100 align:middle line:84%
and then m will move
to the other side.

00:52:54.100 --> 00:52:55.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:55.780 --> 00:53:01.150 align:middle line:84%
So due to different
conventions of the Minkowski

00:53:01.150 --> 00:53:04.780 align:middle line:84%
metric signature you use, et
cetera, so different books

00:53:04.780 --> 00:53:08.990 align:middle line:84%
or different places, you will
see i in different places.

00:53:08.990 --> 00:53:10.780 align:middle line:90%
Some equations have i--

00:53:10.780 --> 00:53:12.430 align:middle line:90%
yeah, some books have i here.

00:53:12.430 --> 00:53:14.710 align:middle line:90%
Some books have i here.

00:53:14.710 --> 00:53:16.855 align:middle line:90%
In my version, there's no i, OK?

00:53:16.855 --> 00:53:17.410 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:17.410 --> 00:53:22.330 align:middle line:84%
And so I know this is
annoying, but yeah,

00:53:22.330 --> 00:53:24.530 align:middle line:90%
but this is just a fact of life.

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:25.030 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:53:25.030 --> 00:53:27.160 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so I find
that this version

00:53:27.160 --> 00:53:30.430 align:middle line:84%
is most simplest in
terms of notation

00:53:30.430 --> 00:53:33.340 align:middle line:84%
anyway, so that's the
convention we use.

00:53:33.340 --> 00:53:36.810 align:middle line:90%


00:53:36.810 --> 00:53:39.010 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:53:39.010 --> 00:53:41.510 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:53:41.510 --> 00:53:44.360 align:middle line:84%
So now, again, this
is a matrix equation.

00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:47.390 align:middle line:84%
Now let me just write it
in the component form,

00:53:47.390 --> 00:53:50.390 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is in
the component form.

00:53:50.390 --> 00:53:54.180 align:middle line:90%
I have gamma mu, which--

00:53:54.180 --> 00:53:58.080 align:middle line:84%
each of them is a matrix,
alpha, beta, so alpha and beta,

00:53:58.080 --> 00:53:58.980 align:middle line:90%
they're always run.

00:53:58.980 --> 00:54:01.320 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sorry for this.

00:54:01.320 --> 00:54:04.560 align:middle line:84%
Now the alpha, beta
just means the--

00:54:04.560 --> 00:54:09.910 align:middle line:84%
yeah, means the indices,
OK, not the matrices.

00:54:09.910 --> 00:54:11.970 align:middle line:90%
So alpha and the beta--

00:54:11.970 --> 00:54:15.420 align:middle line:84%
actually, convention is
to write this like that.

00:54:15.420 --> 00:54:16.980 align:middle line:90%
OK, it doesn't matter.

00:54:16.980 --> 00:54:25.400 align:middle line:84%
So partial mu psi beta minus
m psi alpha equal to 0, OK,

00:54:25.400 --> 00:54:28.160 align:middle line:90%
so this is a matrix equation.

00:54:28.160 --> 00:54:30.150 align:middle line:84%
There are all together
four equations,

00:54:30.150 --> 00:54:35.180 align:middle line:84%
so the beta is summed
because beta is repeated.

00:54:35.180 --> 00:54:40.460 align:middle line:84%
So beta is summed,
and then, yeah,

00:54:40.460 --> 00:54:42.770 align:middle line:90%
and the mu is also summed.

00:54:42.770 --> 00:54:44.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is a little
bit intricate equation.

00:54:44.810 --> 00:54:46.768 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is a little
bit intricate equation,

00:54:46.768 --> 00:54:51.280 align:middle line:84%
but once you get used to it,
it's not that difficult. Yes?

00:54:51.280 --> 00:54:53.280 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There's no
meaning to the upstairsness

00:54:53.280 --> 00:54:56.553 align:middle line:84%
or downstairsness of
alpha and beta, right?

00:54:56.553 --> 00:54:58.470 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: There's a
meaning of upstairs, yeah,

00:54:58.470 --> 00:55:03.790 align:middle line:84%
because these two index
are not symmetric,

00:55:03.790 --> 00:55:07.350 align:middle line:84%
so it's easier to put one
upstairs, one downstairs.

00:55:07.350 --> 00:55:11.520 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, these two indices
are not symmetric.

00:55:11.520 --> 00:55:12.020 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:55:12.020 --> 00:55:12.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:12.520 --> 00:55:17.360 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, it takes a little bit
time to get used to it, OK,

00:55:17.360 --> 00:55:22.250 align:middle line:84%
and I know some people
develop psychological fears

00:55:22.250 --> 00:55:26.510 align:middle line:84%
for fermions because you have to
deal with those gamma matrices,

00:55:26.510 --> 00:55:28.850 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:55:28.850 --> 00:55:31.280 align:middle line:84%
For a long while, actually, I
have this psychological fear

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:31.780 align:middle line:90%
myself.

00:55:31.780 --> 00:55:32.850 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:32.850 --> 00:55:35.780 align:middle line:84%
When I look at fermions,
I want to be away from it

00:55:35.780 --> 00:55:38.330 align:middle line:84%
because I don't want to deal
with those gamma matrices,

00:55:38.330 --> 00:55:43.370 align:middle line:84%
but these are beautiful objects
if you get used to them.

00:55:43.370 --> 00:55:46.220 align:middle line:90%


00:55:46.220 --> 00:55:50.420 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now those
conditions, you can also

00:55:50.420 --> 00:55:54.200 align:middle line:84%
write them in the compact
way in terms of the gamma--

00:55:54.200 --> 00:55:56.150 align:middle line:90%
in terms of gamma matrices.

00:55:56.150 --> 00:56:02.960 align:middle line:84%
OK, so 1, 2, 3 now
can be written as--

00:56:02.960 --> 00:56:07.010 align:middle line:84%
in terms of gamma
matrices gamma mu gamma

00:56:07.010 --> 00:56:10.620 align:middle line:90%
nu plus gamma nu gamma mu.

00:56:10.620 --> 00:56:18.980 align:middle line:84%
So mu nu is always from 0 to 3,
OK, equal to 0, or mu not equal

00:56:18.980 --> 00:56:25.180 align:middle line:84%
to nu, and then gamma 0
squared is equal to minus 1.

00:56:25.180 --> 00:56:28.150 align:middle line:84%
It's because this
gamma 0 is i beta,

00:56:28.150 --> 00:56:30.100 align:middle line:84%
and the beta squared
is equal to 1.

00:56:30.100 --> 00:56:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And then the gamma i square,
so there's no summation over i

00:56:34.630 --> 00:56:38.480 align:middle line:84%
here, OK, because each matrix
gamma i square equal to 1.

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:38.980 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:38.980 --> 00:56:41.690 align:middle line:90%


00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:47.107 align:middle line:84%
And you can write this further
in a more compact form.

00:56:47.107 --> 00:56:49.190 align:middle line:84%
You can write this further
in a more compact form.

00:56:49.190 --> 00:57:09.380 align:middle line:90%


00:57:09.380 --> 00:57:14.050 align:middle line:84%
So you can write this
more compactly as gamma mu

00:57:14.050 --> 00:57:19.450 align:middle line:84%
gamma nu anticommutator
equal to 2 eta mu nu.

00:57:19.450 --> 00:57:22.180 align:middle line:84%
So anti-commutator
just means that if you

00:57:22.180 --> 00:57:28.990 align:middle line:84%
have objects, two objects, curly
bracket means a b plus b a, OK?

00:57:28.990 --> 00:57:31.615 align:middle line:90%
So this is the key equation.

00:57:31.615 --> 00:57:34.300 align:middle line:90%


00:57:34.300 --> 00:57:36.580 align:middle line:84%
OK, so all the gamma
matrices, so you

00:57:36.580 --> 00:57:42.850 align:middle line:84%
can check yourself, OK, all
these are given by just this.

00:57:42.850 --> 00:57:46.280 align:middle line:84%
You can easily see, when mu
not equal to nu, of course,

00:57:46.280 --> 00:57:48.430 align:middle line:84%
the right-hand side
is 0, so that just

00:57:48.430 --> 00:57:50.320 align:middle line:90%
is equal to that equation.

00:57:50.320 --> 00:57:54.940 align:middle line:84%
When mu equal to nu, when
there is-- when they're both 0,

00:57:54.940 --> 00:57:56.680 align:middle line:90%
then this gives you minus 1.

00:57:56.680 --> 00:57:59.080 align:middle line:84%
That's corresponding
to the gamma 0 case,

00:57:59.080 --> 00:58:03.081 align:middle line:84%
and then when they're ij,
then corresponding to gamma x.

00:58:03.081 --> 00:58:03.581 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:03.581 --> 00:58:06.738 align:middle line:90%


00:58:06.738 --> 00:58:09.920 align:middle line:84%
And so this equation, when
the later mathematicians,

00:58:09.920 --> 00:58:13.680 align:middle line:84%
of course, studied
this, a mathematician

00:58:13.680 --> 00:58:15.930 align:middle line:84%
would say this is
a beautiful object.

00:58:15.930 --> 00:58:18.060 align:middle line:84%
And then they studied
this, so now it's

00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:19.065 align:middle line:90%
called Clifford algebra.

00:58:19.065 --> 00:58:21.600 align:middle line:90%


00:58:21.600 --> 00:58:24.135 align:middle line:84%
So this object is
called Clifford algebra.

00:58:24.135 --> 00:58:27.645 align:middle line:90%


00:58:27.645 --> 00:58:29.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:29.970 --> 00:58:38.370 align:middle line:84%
And so then any
sets of gamma mu--

00:58:38.370 --> 00:58:45.540 align:middle line:84%
so gamma mu are a set of
four matrices satisfying this

00:58:45.540 --> 00:58:47.920 align:middle line:90%
equation--

00:58:47.920 --> 00:58:51.280 align:middle line:90%
OK, so let me call this star--

00:58:51.280 --> 00:58:53.800 align:middle line:90%


00:58:53.800 --> 00:59:07.340 align:middle line:84%
is called a representation
of the algebra,

00:59:07.340 --> 00:59:10.820 align:middle line:90%
of the Clifford algebra.

00:59:10.820 --> 00:59:11.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:11.320 --> 00:59:17.970 align:middle line:90%


00:59:17.970 --> 00:59:20.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:20.440 --> 00:59:30.720 align:middle line:84%
So from these two solutions
of alpha and beta,

00:59:30.720 --> 00:59:32.940 align:middle line:84%
we can easily-- from
here, we can work out

00:59:32.940 --> 00:59:40.740 align:middle line:84%
what is the gamma nu and
the gamma i, so yeah,

00:59:40.740 --> 00:59:44.400 align:middle line:90%
so here are two examples.

00:59:44.400 --> 00:59:46.920 align:middle line:84%
Also, yeah, before-- talking
about examples, also,

00:59:46.920 --> 00:59:59.580 align:middle line:84%
from number 4, you also
find that the gamma 0

00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:03.810 align:middle line:84%
dagger equal to minus
gamma 0, and gamma--

01:00:03.810 --> 01:00:09.180 align:middle line:84%
so gamma 0 is anti-Hermitian
and the gamma i is Hermitian.

01:00:09.180 --> 01:00:10.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:10.350 --> 01:00:15.000 align:middle line:84%
And you can also write
this together in the more--

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:21.690 align:middle line:84%
or equivalently write it
as gamma mu dagger gamma

01:00:21.690 --> 01:00:24.120 align:middle line:90%
0 gamma mu gamma 0.

01:00:24.120 --> 01:00:28.330 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you can check that
this equation is the same

01:00:28.330 --> 01:00:29.490 align:middle line:90%
as these two equations.

01:00:29.490 --> 01:00:32.245 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:32.245 --> 01:00:32.745 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:00:32.745 --> 01:00:34.530 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do these
representations

01:00:34.530 --> 01:00:38.520 align:middle line:84%
