Good?

01:03:07.710 --> 01:03:14.240 align:middle line:90%


01:03:14.240 --> 01:03:20.635 align:middle line:90%
So now let me make some remarks.

01:03:20.635 --> 01:03:28.350 align:middle line:90%


01:03:28.350 --> 01:03:39.300 align:middle line:84%
OK, so first, if you consider
the case m equal to 0,

01:03:39.300 --> 01:03:43.950 align:middle line:84%
OK, if you can see the case m
equal to 0, and then this is,

01:03:43.950 --> 01:03:49.410 align:middle line:84%
like, for massless, so
when m equal to zero, then

01:03:49.410 --> 01:03:51.870 align:middle line:84%
when you reduce to this
Klein-Gordon equation, what you

01:03:51.870 --> 01:03:53.340 align:middle line:90%
get is the massless equation.

01:03:53.340 --> 01:03:54.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:54.710 --> 01:03:59.010 align:middle line:84%
OK, it's a massless
equation, and then you

01:03:59.010 --> 01:04:04.140 align:middle line:84%
will have dispersion relation
p squared equal to 0.

01:04:04.140 --> 01:04:09.370 align:middle line:84%
OK, so in this case,
the original equation

01:04:09.370 --> 01:04:13.960 align:middle line:84%
just becomes partial t
equal to minus i alpha

01:04:13.960 --> 01:04:17.860 align:middle line:90%
i partial partial xi psi.

01:04:17.860 --> 01:04:19.570 align:middle line:90%
OK, so that's your equation.

01:04:19.570 --> 01:04:23.140 align:middle line:90%
There's no this m beta term.

01:04:23.140 --> 01:04:24.220 align:middle line:90%
There's no m beta term.

01:04:24.220 --> 01:04:27.060 align:middle line:90%


01:04:27.060 --> 01:04:30.100 align:middle line:90%
So in this case, you just--

01:04:30.100 --> 01:04:33.950 align:middle line:84%
the same story just here,
you just forget about beta.

01:04:33.950 --> 01:04:35.800 align:middle line:84%
OK, the same story,
you forget the beta,

01:04:35.800 --> 01:04:41.590 align:middle line:84%
and then you only
need alpha i alpha

01:04:41.590 --> 01:04:49.060 align:middle line:84%
j the commutator to be 0 for
i not equal to j, essentially

01:04:49.060 --> 01:04:51.310 align:middle line:90%
just that equation 1 there.

01:04:51.310 --> 01:04:56.320 align:middle line:84%
And then also, you'd want the
alpha i square equal to 1, OK,

01:04:56.320 --> 01:04:58.240 align:middle line:90%
so for any i.

01:04:58.240 --> 01:05:05.990 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now these are the
conditions for the alphas,

01:05:05.990 --> 01:05:09.300 align:middle line:84%
and now you can actually
satisfy by 2-by-2 matrices.

01:05:09.300 --> 01:05:12.523 align:middle line:84%
So what matrix satisfies
this kind of relation?

01:05:12.523 --> 01:05:13.190 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Pauli.

01:05:13.190 --> 01:05:16.490 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah, so
the Pauli matrices

01:05:16.490 --> 01:05:19.940 align:middle line:84%
anticommute among themselves,
and their square is equal to 1.

01:05:19.940 --> 01:05:24.800 align:middle line:84%
So you can just take off i
in order to simplify here.

01:05:24.800 --> 01:05:29.630 align:middle line:84%
So this tells you something
important, tells you actually

01:05:29.630 --> 01:05:31.610 align:middle line:84%
the equation for a
massless particle

01:05:31.610 --> 01:05:34.550 align:middle line:84%
and a massive particle
are very different.

01:05:34.550 --> 01:05:36.470 align:middle line:84%
So massive particle,
